sec.p:
Assessing the treatment efficacy of the lamps is less intuitive but of greater clinical importance than their ability to mimic daylight visually. Factors that determine the appropriateness of a lamp include a number of optical characteristics of the lamp:


the light emitted in the spectral region which produces the desired biological effects;

the irradiance and distribution of the light on the retina;

visual discomfort due to flicker, brightness or unnatural colour and

the potential to cause harm to the skin or the eye.

Guidelines issued by the International Commission on Non-Ionizing Radiation Protection (ICNIRP) set out a range of mechanisms for ocular tissue damage arising from non-laser optical radiation:9,10


cataracts and corneal damage similar to sun burn caused by UVR;

retinal damage initiated through photochemical reactions due to UVR and visible light;

retinal burns due to heating from absorbed visible and infrared (IR) radiation and

corneal and lens burns from IR radiation.
